  "prompt": "Why all planets are circling the sun in the same direction?",
  "response": "All the planets in our solar system orbit the Sun in the same direction due to the way our solar system was formed. This uniform motion arises from the conservation of angular momentum and the initial conditions of the solar nebula. Here's an outline of the process:\n\n1. **Formation of the Solar System**: About 4.6 billion years ago, the solar system formed from a giant rotating cloud of gas and dust called the solar nebula. Gravity caused the nebula to collapse inward, forming the Sun at the center.\n\n2. **Conservation of Angular Momentum**: As the solar nebula collapsed, it spun faster due to the conservation of angular momentum. This principle states that if a rotating object decreases in size, its rotation speed must increase. Consequently, the entire cloud began to flatten into a rotating disk with the Sun forming at its center.\n\n3. **Protoplanetary Disk**: The planets formed from this rotating disk of gas and dust. As particles within the disk collided and stuck together, they gradually built up into planetesimals and eventually, planets. The rotation of the disk dictated the direction in which these planetesimals orbited the Sun.\n\n4. **Uniform Rotational Direction**: Because all of the material within the protoplanetary disk was rotating in the same direction due to the initial angular momentum of the collapsing nebula, the forming planets naturally ended up orbiting in the same direction.\n\nIn summary, the reason all planets orbit the Sun in the same direction stems from the conservation of angular momentum and the rotation of the protoplanetary disk during the formation of the solar system.",
